WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.300 --> 00:00:03.867
RONALD SMITH: OK, so we're going
to do the stratospheric

00:00:03.867 --> 00:00:07.133
ozone problem today.

00:00:07.133 --> 00:00:12.833
And these are the new
terminology you

00:00:12.833 --> 00:00:13.833
should be aware of.

00:00:13.833 --> 00:00:19.367
So we'll talk about the ozone
layer and then the ozone hole.

00:00:19.367 --> 00:00:23.767
The Dobson unit I'll discuss,
I'll define as a measure of

00:00:23.767 --> 00:00:27.667
column integrated ozone
concentration.

00:00:27.667 --> 00:00:32.400
We'll be talking about CFCs
which had been used as the

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:37.333
primary liquid in
refrigerators.

00:00:37.333 --> 00:00:40.700
And you need to have a fluid
that flows back and forth

00:00:40.700 --> 00:00:45.100
between the cold sink and the
warm sink in a refrigerator.

00:00:45.100 --> 00:00:51.800
And CFCs was the common
chemical to do that.

00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:58.967
But now they've been replaced
largely by HCFCs, the

00:00:58.967 --> 00:01:00.767
hydrochlorofluorocarbons.

00:01:00.767 --> 00:01:05.900
Say that 10 times fast. And so
I'll define those as well.

00:01:05.900 --> 00:01:08.733
We'll talk at some point today
about polar stratospheric

00:01:08.733 --> 00:01:13.667
clouds, catalytic reactions,
which are reactions in which

00:01:13.667 --> 00:01:17.400
one particular chemical compound
allows the reaction

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:22.267
to go forward but in the end
itself isn't changed.

00:01:22.267 --> 00:01:25.733
So it can be reused over and
over again to make the same

00:01:25.733 --> 00:01:27.933
chemical cycle go forward.

00:01:27.933 --> 00:01:30.267
Photochemical reactions, which
are chemical reactions that

00:01:30.267 --> 00:01:31.567
involve light.

00:01:31.567 --> 00:01:34.133
You have to have photons of
light in order for that

00:01:34.133 --> 00:01:36.133
reaction to go forward.

00:01:36.133 --> 00:01:37.933
And we'll talk about the
Montreal Protocol.

00:01:37.933 --> 00:01:42.467
So all this will come
in turn today.

00:01:42.467 --> 00:01:46.233
First of all, I showed this
diagram last time as we

00:01:46.233 --> 00:01:49.900
discussed this part of the ozone
issue, but now we're

00:01:49.900 --> 00:01:51.667
going to talk about
the ozone layer.

00:01:51.667 --> 00:01:56.133
And as it says here, contains
90% of the atmospheric ozone.

00:01:56.133 --> 00:01:59.300
So if you do a column
integration from the top of

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:03.200
the atmosphere to the bottom,
most of the contribution comes

00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:05.567
from the ozone layer.

00:02:05.567 --> 00:02:11.500
What's plotted here is the
partial pressure of ozone in

00:02:11.500 --> 00:02:12.767
milliPascals.

00:02:14.600 --> 00:02:20.667
Remember that the total
pressure, the air pressure,

00:02:20.667 --> 00:02:24.100
decreases strongly and
exponentially all the way on

00:02:24.100 --> 00:02:26.600
up through the troposphere
and the stratosphere.

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:29.967
So this has a very different
vertical structure than the

00:02:29.967 --> 00:02:33.467
total pressure.

00:02:33.467 --> 00:02:38.267
It has a beneficial role, it
acts as a shield against

00:02:38.267 --> 00:02:42.033
ultraviolet radiation that would
otherwise cause skin

00:02:42.033 --> 00:02:44.733
cancer, skin damage.

00:02:44.733 --> 00:02:50.467
And the current trends are a
long-term global downtrend in

00:02:50.467 --> 00:02:51.700
stratospheric ozone.

00:02:54.200 --> 00:02:59.800
And then most famously, this
ozone hole which occurs in the

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:06.067
springtime of the Antarctic part
of the earth each year.

00:03:06.067 --> 00:03:08.933
And then some more recent
discussion about possibly this

00:03:08.933 --> 00:03:11.733
starting up in the Northern
Hemisphere as well, but this

00:03:11.733 --> 00:03:13.700
is not as well documented.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.433
So just a couple of
calculations then.

00:03:21.433 --> 00:03:32.067
So I want to compute the mixing
ratio in ppmv for ozone

00:03:32.067 --> 00:03:36.967
to air using this point
on this slide.

00:03:36.967 --> 00:03:42.967
So I'm going to say that at
about 24 kilometers altitude

00:03:42.967 --> 00:03:46.967
you've got a partial pressure
of ozone that's about 30

00:03:46.967 --> 00:03:48.233
milliPascals.

00:03:48.233 --> 00:03:50.567
And I want to convert that to a
mixing ratio because that's

00:03:50.567 --> 00:03:55.500
what we've been used to using,
what we used last time.

00:03:55.500 --> 00:03:58.700
So first of all, because it's
going to be a mixing ratio you

00:03:58.700 --> 00:04:02.033
need to know how much air is up
there as well, not just how

00:04:02.033 --> 00:04:03.400
much ozone, but how much air.

00:04:03.400 --> 00:04:06.100
So I'm going to use this simple
formula that we've used

00:04:06.100 --> 00:04:07.767
quite often in the course.

00:04:07.767 --> 00:04:13.633
It's the approximate exponential
form for pressure

00:04:13.633 --> 00:04:18.300
as a function of altitude
where you use a scale

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:20.467
height, H sub s.

00:04:20.467 --> 00:04:23.233
You know the pressure at the
surface of the earth, you know

00:04:23.233 --> 00:04:25.967
the altitude you're inquiring
about, and this will give you

00:04:25.967 --> 00:04:27.200
the pressure at that altitude

00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:31.833
So sea level pressure we'll take
to be 1,013 millibars,

00:04:31.833 --> 00:04:34.200
which is the standard
average value,

00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:35.933
convert that to Pascals.

00:04:35.933 --> 00:04:40.433
The scale height as you recall
is RT over g, which is about

00:04:40.433 --> 00:04:44.800
8,400 meters for the earth--the
earth's atmosphere.

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:49.533
So I'll put 24 kilometers up
here, that scale height there,

00:04:49.533 --> 00:04:52.867
and I'll put the sea level
pressure there, and that's

00:04:52.867 --> 00:04:53.733
this formula here.

00:04:53.733 --> 00:04:58.100
So I put everything where I said
I would and I get a value

00:04:58.100 --> 00:05:06.933
of about 6,000 Pascals for
the air pressure up here.

00:05:06.933 --> 00:05:11.600
And then I can simply put that
into a ratio of the two

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:17.267
pressures to get the mixing
ratio in the common units.

00:05:17.267 --> 00:05:27.200
So I put in that the value of
0.03/6,000, I get 20 ppmv for

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:33.967
the ozone mixing ratio in the
peak of the ozone layer.

00:05:33.967 --> 00:05:35.400
OK?

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:37.400
Pretty straightforward
calculation.

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:39.933
Had to find out how much air
was there and then from the

00:05:39.933 --> 00:05:43.067
proper ratio get it in
the proper units.

00:05:43.067 --> 00:05:45.100
Now compare this to what we were
talking about last time.

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:50.367
The EPA one hour standard for
ozone in the boundary layer,

00:05:50.367 --> 00:05:56.500
where we live, was 0.12
in those same units.

00:05:56.500 --> 00:06:02.400
So the ozone concentration in
the ozone layer is about 200

00:06:02.400 --> 00:06:09.200
times the EPA one hour limit,
just to give you a relative

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:10.067
sense for that.

00:06:10.067 --> 00:06:15.300
So if we were up there, that
would be really tough for us

00:06:15.300 --> 00:06:16.133
to breathe that in.

00:06:16.133 --> 00:06:18.900
Now remember however, there's
not enough air to keep us

00:06:18.900 --> 00:06:22.233
alive anyway at those
altitudes.

00:06:22.233 --> 00:06:25.700
But the ozone concentration
is quite large as well.

00:06:25.700 --> 00:06:29.467
So that's an inhospitable
environment up

00:06:29.467 --> 00:06:30.867
there at that altitude.

00:06:30.867 --> 00:06:32.100
Any questions on that?

00:06:37.833 --> 00:06:41.533
But it is possible, or it was
until recently, possible for

00:06:41.533 --> 00:06:46.100
us to fly at those altitudes.

00:06:46.100 --> 00:06:51.067
So the Concorde, this beautiful,
supersonic,

00:06:51.067 --> 00:06:53.533
commercial airliner which
stopped flying a couple years

00:06:53.533 --> 00:06:59.733
ago, it flew at an altitude
typically of 17 kilometers,

00:06:59.733 --> 00:07:02.500
which isn't quite at the peak
of the ozone concentration,

00:07:02.500 --> 00:07:05.467
but it's definitely up in the
ozone layer, there's no doubt

00:07:05.467 --> 00:07:07.067
about that.

00:07:07.067 --> 00:07:09.567
And of course, you have to
refresh the cabin air.

00:07:09.567 --> 00:07:13.833
You can't just lock the cabin
doors and expect everybody to

00:07:13.833 --> 00:07:17.600
live off that cabin air until
you get to your destination.

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:21.367
So the aircraft can continually
draw in air from

00:07:21.367 --> 00:07:26.533
outside to flush the cabin and
give you fresh cabin air.

00:07:26.533 --> 00:07:28.833
The question is how do you
do that in this case?

00:07:31.400 --> 00:07:33.767
Remember though that there's
two problems. First of all,

00:07:33.767 --> 00:07:35.467
there's very little air
outside anyway.

00:07:35.467 --> 00:07:38.767
So you're going to have to
compress it with some kind of

00:07:38.767 --> 00:07:43.133
a pump before you can put it
into the cabin so people can

00:07:43.133 --> 00:07:44.000
breathe it.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.033
And that's going to be
a big compression.

00:07:48.033 --> 00:07:50.000
Let's just think about
this for a minute.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:55.200
So if you're flying at 17
kilometers and you want to get

00:07:55.200 --> 00:08:00.367
that air compressed to cabin
pressure, well first of all

00:08:00.367 --> 00:08:04.867
what cabin pressure do
you normally have?

00:08:04.867 --> 00:08:09.500
Airliners don't usually keep
you at sea level pressure.

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:13.700
If you're taking off from New
York City, as you take off the

00:08:13.700 --> 00:08:15.133
pressure will drop--

00:08:15.133 --> 00:08:18.633
in the cabin will drop as you
climb, but they'll usually

00:08:18.633 --> 00:08:23.667
only let it drop to maybe an
equivalent altitude of 6,000

00:08:23.667 --> 00:08:25.033
feet, something like that.

00:08:25.033 --> 00:08:27.733
Then they couldn't let it go
any lower or you'd start to

00:08:27.733 --> 00:08:29.933
have trouble breathing,
but they don't

00:08:29.933 --> 00:08:31.900
keep you at sea level.

00:08:31.900 --> 00:08:37.100
So I'm going to assume that the,
for this calculation that

00:08:37.100 --> 00:08:42.967
the cabin altitude, what's
called the cabin altitude, is

00:08:42.967 --> 00:08:44.833
going to be kept at
2 kilometers.

00:08:44.833 --> 00:08:49.467
That's about 6,000 feet
above the surface.

00:08:49.467 --> 00:08:52.167
In fact, you're flying at 17
kilometers, so you've got to

00:08:52.167 --> 00:08:55.533
take air and compress it just
as you would if you took a

00:08:55.533 --> 00:08:58.833
parcel of air from 17 kilometers
and brought it down

00:08:58.833 --> 00:09:02.233
to two kilometers, it would
compress, adiabatic

00:09:02.233 --> 00:09:03.833
compression, we've
talked about this

00:09:03.833 --> 00:09:04.767
over and over again.

00:09:04.767 --> 00:09:07.700
And it would heat as
you compress it.

00:09:07.700 --> 00:09:11.167
So when you put it into that
pump and compress it, it's

00:09:11.167 --> 00:09:12.700
going to warm up,
and how much?

00:09:12.700 --> 00:09:14.967
Well this is a calculation
you can do in your head.

00:09:14.967 --> 00:09:19.633
You know the adiabatic lapse
rate is about 10 degrees per

00:09:19.633 --> 00:09:23.500
kilometer, actually it's 9.8,
but I've rounded it off.

00:09:23.500 --> 00:09:26.500
That's a difference in 15
kilometers, so essentially

00:09:26.500 --> 00:09:31.500
you're going to get 150 degrees
Celsius warming when

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:34.600
you compress that air
about ready to

00:09:34.600 --> 00:09:35.567
put it into the cabin.

00:09:35.567 --> 00:09:39.100
Now you're going to--it started
off pretty cold, but

00:09:39.100 --> 00:09:43.000
still that's going to
be really hot air.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:44.167
Two things I've got
to say about that.

00:09:44.167 --> 00:09:47.433
First of all, the convenient
thing is that that temperature

00:09:47.433 --> 00:09:50.133
will destroy the ozone.

00:09:50.133 --> 00:09:53.767
So just by compressing the air,
getting it ready to put

00:09:53.767 --> 00:09:56.767
into the cabin, you're going
to kill off that ozone

00:09:56.767 --> 00:09:58.100
automatically.

00:09:58.100 --> 00:09:59.400
So that's pretty convenient.

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:01.533
But then remember, you're going
to have to cool it a bit

00:10:01.533 --> 00:10:03.900
before you put it
into the cabin.

00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:05.533
So you're going to put it
through another heat

00:10:05.533 --> 00:10:09.267
exchanger, cool it back down,
and then you get the air to

00:10:09.267 --> 00:10:11.233
stick into the cabin.

00:10:11.233 --> 00:10:14.600
If you don't get it all out, you
can pass the air through

00:10:14.600 --> 00:10:19.533
an activated charcoal filter
and that will remove any

00:10:19.533 --> 00:10:22.900
remaining ozone that's
in the air before you

00:10:22.900 --> 00:10:23.833
put it into the cabin.

00:10:23.833 --> 00:10:27.200
So it is possible to fly at
those altitudes right in the

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:28.233
middle of the ozone layer.

00:10:28.233 --> 00:10:30.900
But that's how you
have to do it.

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:32.333
Any questions on that?

00:10:32.333 --> 00:10:33.033
Yeah?

00:10:33.033 --> 00:10:34.100
STUDENT: Why would you
want to fly at

00:10:34.100 --> 00:10:36.833
that high of an altitude?

00:10:36.833 --> 00:10:38.633
PROFESSOR: It turns out it has
mostly to do with

00:10:38.633 --> 00:10:41.500
the efficiency of the engines.

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:44.467
In fact, that's true with
subsonic aircraft as well.

00:10:44.467 --> 00:10:49.300
The reason they fly quite high,
35,000 feet, 37,000 feet

00:10:49.300 --> 00:10:50.767
is because the engines are most

00:10:50.767 --> 00:10:52.700
efficient at that altitude.

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:54.800
And for this aircraft, the more
efficient--the altitude

00:10:54.800 --> 00:10:59.200
was even higher at
17 kilometers.

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:02.500
So anything on that?

00:11:02.500 --> 00:11:06.600
OK, maybe that's a little
tangential point, but--

00:11:06.600 --> 00:11:11.233
This thing called the Dobson
unit is a column density.

00:11:11.233 --> 00:11:15.300
We could write it, in fact, I
wish that they had chosen the

00:11:15.300 --> 00:11:18.267
unit of kilograms per
square meter.

00:11:18.267 --> 00:11:22.367
You'd simply integrate top to
bottom in the atmosphere and

00:11:22.367 --> 00:11:26.467
say how many kilograms of ozone
are there in each square

00:11:26.467 --> 00:11:29.733
meter of footprint for
that column that

00:11:29.733 --> 00:11:30.667
you've integrated over.

00:11:30.667 --> 00:11:34.667
But for historic reasons they
didn't do it that way.

00:11:34.667 --> 00:11:38.967
This is typically measured by
looking at light coming from

00:11:38.967 --> 00:11:42.300
the sun and see how much
ultraviolet light reaches the

00:11:42.300 --> 00:11:44.767
surface of the earth.

00:11:44.767 --> 00:11:46.400
And that will tell you
how much ozone

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:48.800
there is in the column.

00:11:48.800 --> 00:11:51.067
What they're using for the
Dobson unit is this

00:11:51.067 --> 00:11:54.967
definition, it's 1
milli-atmosphere-centimeters.

00:11:54.967 --> 00:11:58.633
That's the scientific definition
of a Dobson unit.

00:11:58.633 --> 00:12:00.367
And here's how you
think about that.

00:12:00.367 --> 00:12:04.300
You take all the ozone in the
column, you compress it to

00:12:04.300 --> 00:12:07.767
standard temperature and
pressure, that is 1 atmosphere

00:12:07.767 --> 00:12:12.267
of pressure and 0
degrees Celsius.

00:12:12.267 --> 00:12:16.900
And then you measure how thick
that layer would be composed

00:12:16.900 --> 00:12:20.867
just of ozone and you measure
that in thousandth of a

00:12:20.867 --> 00:12:22.200
centimeter.

00:12:22.200 --> 00:12:27.067
And that is your Dobson
unit value.

00:12:27.067 --> 00:12:28.967
And I'll be showing you
this kind of data.

00:12:28.967 --> 00:12:32.667
Typical values for the earth's
atmosphere run from 100 to 500

00:12:32.667 --> 00:12:34.867
Dobson units depending
on where you

00:12:34.867 --> 00:12:36.600
are around the world.

00:12:36.600 --> 00:12:39.000
But that is normally--

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.900
the Dobson is what we use to
describe to each other how

00:12:42.900 --> 00:12:46.367
much ozone there is
in the atmosphere.

00:12:46.367 --> 00:12:50.333
So for example, you'll see a
diagram like this from NASA.

00:12:50.333 --> 00:12:53.200
It's a map of the world and
some areas are blocked out

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:56.567
because they don't have data
from here for this particular

00:12:56.567 --> 00:12:58.067
time of year.

00:12:58.067 --> 00:13:02.433
But the scale is in
Dobson units.

00:13:02.433 --> 00:13:06.667
So in the tropical regions
you're getting values of about

00:13:06.667 --> 00:13:10.300
250, 260 Dobson units.

00:13:10.300 --> 00:13:14.267
In the green you're getting
values maybe 325, maybe in

00:13:14.267 --> 00:13:16.667
some areas even 350 or 360.

00:13:16.667 --> 00:13:24.300
So that's the way we represent
column integrated ozone in

00:13:24.300 --> 00:13:26.867
this subject.

00:13:26.867 --> 00:13:30.600
We can also get vertical profile
information either by

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:34.000
direct in situ measurements or
by looking at light passing

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.767
across the earth's atmosphere
horizontally.

00:13:37.767 --> 00:13:41.000
This gives you some idea where
the ozone layer is as a

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:42.600
function of latitude.

00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:45.967
So here's latitude,
North Pole, South

00:13:45.967 --> 00:13:48.300
Pole, Equator, altitude.

00:13:48.300 --> 00:13:51.400
But notice the offset 0, this
isn't the ground, this is

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:54.933
starting at 16 kilometers,
right?

00:13:54.933 --> 00:14:03.433
So the ozone layer at higher
latitudes, it peaks at an

00:14:03.433 --> 00:14:08.500
altitude of about 20 kilometers,
18, 19, 20

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:09.200
kilometers.

00:14:09.200 --> 00:14:15.300
But near the Equator, it's up
around 25, 26 kilometers.

00:14:15.300 --> 00:14:17.500
I think we expected this
because remember the

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:20.867
tropopause has the same
kind of a structure.

00:14:20.867 --> 00:14:24.300
It's higher in the equatorial
regions and lower

00:14:24.300 --> 00:14:26.467
in the polar regions.

00:14:26.467 --> 00:14:31.133
So the ozone layer is about
the same place in the

00:14:31.133 --> 00:14:34.000
stratosphere, but the
stratosphere starts at a

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:35.267
different level.

00:14:35.267 --> 00:14:39.033
So it's lifted in a sense
relative to the surface of the

00:14:39.033 --> 00:14:46.100
earth in the equatorial
latitudes.

00:14:46.100 --> 00:14:47.167
The reason why--part of the
reason why there is that

00:14:47.167 --> 00:14:50.433
difference is because of a broad
circulation that takes

00:14:50.433 --> 00:14:54.367
place in the stratosphere calls
call the Brewer-Dobson

00:14:54.367 --> 00:14:57.867
circulation, which I won't talk
about, but this artist

00:14:57.867 --> 00:15:02.267
has reminded us that there is
this broad slow circulation in

00:15:02.267 --> 00:15:03.500
the stratosphere.

00:15:05.367 --> 00:15:10.433
So why do we have ozone
in the stratosphere?

00:15:10.433 --> 00:15:13.967
This is a basic chemistry
of that.

00:15:13.967 --> 00:15:17.733
We know we have a lot of O2 in
our atmosphere, it's the

00:15:17.733 --> 00:15:20.900
second most common molecule.

00:15:20.900 --> 00:15:23.967
And occasionally, a high
energy photon will

00:15:23.967 --> 00:15:24.867
come from the sun.

00:15:24.867 --> 00:15:30.767
A high energy ultraviolet photon
will dissociate that

00:15:30.767 --> 00:15:35.733
diatomic oxygen into two oxygen
atoms. It doesn't

00:15:35.733 --> 00:15:38.033
happen very often because
it needs a high energy

00:15:38.033 --> 00:15:39.733
photon to do that.

00:15:39.733 --> 00:15:44.500
But then you've got some free
oxygen atoms floating around.

00:15:44.500 --> 00:15:47.767
And when you have that, that'll
quickly combine with

00:15:47.767 --> 00:15:50.900
an O2 molecule to form ozone.

00:15:50.900 --> 00:15:53.567
That's a fast reaction.

00:15:53.567 --> 00:15:58.700
But equally fast is that other
ultraviolet photons, they

00:15:58.700 --> 00:16:02.700
don't have to be as energetic
as this one, these can be in

00:16:02.700 --> 00:16:08.267
the near, or in the UVA, for
example, the near ultraviolet,

00:16:08.267 --> 00:16:12.033
will dissociate that
back to this again.

00:16:12.033 --> 00:16:12.833
And that's fast.

00:16:12.833 --> 00:16:18.033
So what you've got is a rapid
recycling going on between

00:16:18.033 --> 00:16:23.200
that and that that's just going
out all the time in the

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:26.800
stratosphere, but maintaining
a balance here.

00:16:26.800 --> 00:16:30.833
Now occasionally an ozone will
interact with one of these

00:16:30.833 --> 00:16:35.533
atoms and go back to go to O2,
which is the common form.

00:16:35.533 --> 00:16:37.767
And then you've lost it.

00:16:37.767 --> 00:16:43.500
So you've lost the ozone
permanently or at least quasi

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:44.267
permanently.

00:16:44.267 --> 00:16:49.100
So the ozone concentration is
controlled by--ignoring this

00:16:49.100 --> 00:16:53.500
rapid cycling which doesn't have
any long-term effect, is

00:16:53.500 --> 00:16:56.567
controlled by the balance of
these two slow processes.

00:16:56.567 --> 00:17:01.533
How often are you producing
oxygen atoms and how often are

00:17:01.533 --> 00:17:06.167
you removing ozone and oxygen
atoms back to O2?

00:17:06.167 --> 00:17:08.767
And that would be occurring
naturally because we have

00:17:08.767 --> 00:17:12.300
oxygen in the atmosphere and
we have ultraviolet light

00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:13.933
coming from the sun.

00:17:13.933 --> 00:17:17.800
So that's the background to
why there is ozone in the

00:17:17.800 --> 00:17:19.667
stratosphere.

00:17:19.667 --> 00:17:21.900
The reason why it doesn't happen
further down is because

00:17:21.900 --> 00:17:25.967
most of these ultraviolet
photons are absorbed up there

00:17:25.967 --> 00:17:29.300
and don't get--don't penetrate
deeper into the atmosphere.

00:17:29.300 --> 00:17:32.367
So it's a layer up there because
that's where these

00:17:32.367 --> 00:17:37.233
ultraviolet photons are being
absorbed and doing this work

00:17:37.233 --> 00:17:42.133
causing these photochemical
reactions to take place.

