00:31:14.667 --> 00:31:19.967
So I think the most curious
thing about the ozone hole is

00:31:19.967 --> 00:31:23.667
why only in September
and October?

00:31:23.667 --> 00:31:27.167
Why just over the South Pole?

00:31:27.167 --> 00:31:29.267
And I guess what is the link
to human activity?

00:31:29.267 --> 00:31:32.800
So there's a lot of natural
processes and factors

00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:34.233
controlling this.

00:31:34.233 --> 00:31:38.667
And then there's the added
impact of humans and somehow

00:31:38.667 --> 00:31:43.333
they have all come together to
form this curious phenomena of

00:31:43.333 --> 00:31:44.600
the ozone hole.

00:31:44.600 --> 00:31:47.800
In the few minutes I have left
I want to just try to explain

00:31:47.800 --> 00:31:50.967
some of that.

00:31:50.967 --> 00:31:56.700
Now I hope you can see this,
I'll read it through for you.

00:31:56.700 --> 00:31:59.600
This is the seasonal cycle
of temperature in the

00:31:59.600 --> 00:32:01.267
stratosphere.

00:32:01.267 --> 00:32:07.767
And this is for 90 North
to 65 North, so this is

00:32:07.767 --> 00:32:11.500
the north polar cap.

00:32:11.500 --> 00:32:15.500
This is 25 North to 25
South, so this is

00:32:15.500 --> 00:32:17.533
the equatorial region.

00:32:17.533 --> 00:32:21.767
And this is 65 South to 90
South, so this is the south

00:32:21.767 --> 00:32:23.167
polar region.

00:32:23.167 --> 00:32:28.700
Now the temperatures in the
Northern Hemisphere get down

00:32:28.700 --> 00:32:31.600
to minus 70 on occasion.

00:32:31.600 --> 00:32:35.433
These are at different
altitudes, I believe, having

00:32:35.433 --> 00:32:37.200
trouble reading those.

00:32:37.200 --> 00:32:39.733
They get down to minus 70.

00:32:39.733 --> 00:32:43.100
In the equatorial regions, those
temperatures get down to

00:32:43.100 --> 00:32:46.333
about minus 75.

00:32:46.333 --> 00:32:50.067
But here in the South Pole, they
get down to minus 80 and

00:32:50.067 --> 00:32:52.167
even minus 85.

00:32:52.167 --> 00:32:57.100
So of all the places in the
world's stratosphere, the

00:32:57.100 --> 00:33:00.533
Southern Hemisphere polar
stratosphere, that is over

00:33:00.533 --> 00:33:04.567
Antarctica, has a winter time
temperature colder than any

00:33:04.567 --> 00:33:07.600
other place on the planet.

00:33:07.600 --> 00:33:11.033
That's one of the things that
makes it special in regards to

00:33:11.033 --> 00:33:14.167
why the ozone hole
forms there.

00:33:14.167 --> 00:33:16.800
Now why would that be?

00:33:16.800 --> 00:33:20.000
It has to do with the
phenomena of polar

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:24.033
stratospheric clouds,
abbreviation PSCs.

00:33:27.733 --> 00:33:27.867
Polar stratospheric clouds.

00:33:27.867 --> 00:33:30.067
I haven't spoken about these
in the course up to this

00:33:30.067 --> 00:33:33.100
present time, so this
is new material.

00:33:33.100 --> 00:33:38.633
These are ice clouds that form
up in the stratosphere.

00:33:38.633 --> 00:33:41.567
Normally we think clouds don't
form in the stratosphere, it's

00:33:41.567 --> 00:33:45.800
pretty dry up there, but
these clouds do.

00:33:45.800 --> 00:33:49.100
They are not entirely
made of water.

00:33:49.100 --> 00:33:54.000
They're a mixture of water and
nitric acid in these clouds.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:56.300
And they require an
extraordinarily cold

00:33:56.300 --> 00:34:00.767
temperature in order to form,
temperatures colder than minus

00:34:00.767 --> 00:34:05.167
70 degrees Celsius, some would
say even colder than that.

00:34:05.167 --> 00:34:12.000
This is probably why the
Antarctic stratosphere is so

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:14.433
special because it's temperature
gets cold enough

00:34:14.433 --> 00:34:19.567
in winter to allow these polar
stratospheric clouds to occur,

00:34:19.567 --> 00:34:22.600
whereas other places around the
globe in the stratosphere

00:34:22.600 --> 00:34:25.033
you don't get those clouds.

00:34:25.033 --> 00:34:26.700
What do they do then?

00:34:26.700 --> 00:34:29.867
How do they influence ozone?

00:34:29.867 --> 00:34:36.033
Well these ice clouds, these
ice particles, freeze up

00:34:36.033 --> 00:34:39.767
diatomic chlorine by
holding the nitric

00:34:39.767 --> 00:34:42.367
acid in the ice itself.

00:34:42.367 --> 00:34:48.067
Notice when it forms it's
storing HNO3, nitric acid.

00:34:48.067 --> 00:34:49.567
And here's the reaction.

00:34:49.567 --> 00:34:57.600
You start with HCl, and ClONO2,
reaction goes to Cl2

00:34:57.600 --> 00:35:03.167
and the nitric acid, and then
this is locked up in the ice.

00:35:03.167 --> 00:35:07.700
So what you've done, you had
your chlorine locked up in HCl

00:35:07.700 --> 00:35:11.233
and in this compound, there's
chlorines in both.

00:35:11.233 --> 00:35:15.400
Now you've put the nitric acid
in the ice and you've freed up

00:35:15.400 --> 00:35:18.267
the chlorine diatomic
molecule.

00:35:18.267 --> 00:35:21.967
There's only one step to go.

00:35:21.967 --> 00:35:23.267
When the light returns,
remember, that minimum of

00:35:23.267 --> 00:35:27.700
temperature occurred in
perpetual darkness.

00:35:27.700 --> 00:35:30.733
At that season of the year,
it's dark over Antarctica,

00:35:30.733 --> 00:35:32.200
there's no light.

00:35:32.200 --> 00:35:35.333
So you can get the ice forming,
you can get the Cl

00:35:35.333 --> 00:35:38.500
all ready to go, but it's
in the diatomic form.

00:35:38.500 --> 00:35:42.833
Then the light comes back,
Southern Hemisphere spring,

00:35:42.833 --> 00:35:49.600
the light comes back, you can
dissociate the Cl2 to form two

00:35:49.600 --> 00:35:51.667
Cl molecules.

00:35:51.667 --> 00:35:55.100
And then go back a few slides to
that catalytic reaction and

00:35:55.100 --> 00:35:58.933
it starts to destroy ozone.

00:35:58.933 --> 00:35:59.633
So you get that?

00:35:59.633 --> 00:36:04.100
So the ice frees up the
chlorine, it then dissociates

00:36:04.100 --> 00:36:08.067
when light returns, and the
catalytic destruction of ozone

00:36:08.067 --> 00:36:13.000
begins to take place, and the
ozone hole forms. That's why

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:18.200
it occurs where it does and when
it does because of that

00:36:18.200 --> 00:36:21.533
necessary condition for cold.

00:36:21.533 --> 00:36:29.467
And then the ozone hole forms
just after the light returns

00:36:29.467 --> 00:36:30.700
to that region.

00:36:33.167 --> 00:36:33.833
Any questions on that?

00:36:33.833 --> 00:36:34.700
Yes?.

00:36:34.700 --> 00:36:39.433
STUDENT: Where does the
hydrochloric acid

00:36:39.433 --> 00:36:44.767
come from, the HCl?

00:36:44.767 --> 00:36:46.100
PROFESSOR: I don't know.

00:36:46.100 --> 00:36:49.533
That's the way the chlorine is
stored most of the time in the

00:36:49.533 --> 00:36:53.167
stratosphere, is in these
two molecules.

00:36:53.167 --> 00:36:58.233
After the CFCs break down, the
chlorine is transferred into

00:36:58.233 --> 00:37:02.067
these two forms and
just hangs around.

00:37:02.067 --> 00:37:06.733
Then the PSCs form and that
sucks off the nitric acid and

00:37:06.733 --> 00:37:07.633
the Cl is released.

00:37:07.633 --> 00:37:13.133
So this is the storage form of
the chlorine during most of

00:37:13.133 --> 00:37:15.100
the year in the stratosphere.

00:37:15.100 --> 00:37:17.500
STUDENT: Is there normally
chlorine in the atmosphere

00:37:17.500 --> 00:37:18.733
besides the HCI?

00:37:20.533 --> 00:37:21.433
PROFESSOR: Not naturally.

00:37:21.433 --> 00:37:27.233
Remember this was CFCs
and not chlorine.

00:37:27.233 --> 00:37:28.500
And that's a critical
difference.

00:37:28.500 --> 00:37:31.733
But let me just go
back to that.

00:37:31.733 --> 00:37:36.333
There were no CFCs in the
atmosphere before that.

00:37:36.333 --> 00:37:38.400
There probably was a little bit
of chlorine, but only a

00:37:38.400 --> 00:37:39.733
very small amount.

00:37:39.733 --> 00:37:44.200
But now we're putting it in
through this CFC source.

00:37:44.200 --> 00:37:45.800
Sorry, that's not a complete
answer, but that's

00:37:45.800 --> 00:37:47.067
the best I can do.

00:37:51.700 --> 00:37:55.200
So I think this-yeah, this
is the last one.

00:37:55.200 --> 00:38:00.567
So the Montreal Protocol, the
full name of it is Montreal

00:38:00.567 --> 00:38:04.500
Protocol on Substances that
Deplete the Ozone layer.

00:38:04.500 --> 00:38:06.033
It's an international treaty.

00:38:08.933 --> 00:38:11.533
And of course it was first
signed in Montreal,

00:38:11.533 --> 00:38:12.467
it's got the name.

00:38:12.467 --> 00:38:17.367
Since then it has been modified
several times.

00:38:17.367 --> 00:38:23.100
Certain forms of substances have
been added to the banned

00:38:23.100 --> 00:38:24.400
list, others have
been allowed.

00:38:24.400 --> 00:38:27.300
So it's been modified
a few times.

00:38:27.300 --> 00:38:31.667
Generally what it did is by the
time we came to 1994, it

00:38:31.667 --> 00:38:35.367
had banned pretty much all
emissions of CFCs into the

00:38:35.367 --> 00:38:35.867
atmosphere.

00:38:35.867 --> 00:38:42.800
It largely replaced them with
the HCFC, which can also be

00:38:42.800 --> 00:38:49.333
used as a refrigerant, but has
a much shorter lifetime and

00:38:49.333 --> 00:38:52.867
will not cause the chlorine to
build up in the atmosphere.

00:38:52.867 --> 00:38:55.067
It may have some other
problems, it may be a

00:38:55.067 --> 00:38:56.000
greenhouse gas.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:59.767
But it doesn't have the problem
of putting permanently

00:38:59.767 --> 00:39:03.200
chlorine into the atmosphere
the way that the CFCs do.

00:39:03.200 --> 00:39:07.767
Now one of the reasons why
this treaty was signed,

00:39:07.767 --> 00:39:13.167
because as you'd expect the
refrigerant industry

00:39:13.167 --> 00:39:17.800
vigorously opposed this, was
at about the time it was

00:39:17.800 --> 00:39:21.333
signed, Dupont which was this
large chemical company and the

00:39:21.333 --> 00:39:25.700
world's largest producer
of CFCs, discovered a

00:39:25.700 --> 00:39:28.100
replacement for it.

00:39:28.100 --> 00:39:30.800
And they realized that they
would not lose their business

00:39:30.800 --> 00:39:34.467
because they had a replacement
ready to go and they might

00:39:34.467 --> 00:39:38.567
even be able to make more money
by doing this changeover

00:39:38.567 --> 00:39:40.967
to a different type
of refrigerant.

00:39:40.967 --> 00:39:46.700
So in the end, they dropped
their opposition and many

00:39:46.700 --> 00:39:48.833
countries of the world got
together and signed this

00:39:48.833 --> 00:39:49.800
international treaty.

00:39:49.800 --> 00:39:52.733
And it's viewed in environmental
circles as being

00:39:52.733 --> 00:39:58.733
one of the best examples of a
successful situation where the

00:39:58.733 --> 00:40:03.333
scientists discovered the
problem, suggested how to

00:40:03.333 --> 00:40:06.067
solve it, and then you have
the countries of the world

00:40:06.067 --> 00:40:07.733
actually getting together
to pass a treaty

00:40:07.733 --> 00:40:08.833
and acting on it.

00:40:08.833 --> 00:40:14.000
As you saw, the CFC emissions
have dropped nearly to 0 now.

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:19.933
So it's looked at as, well in
some cases, in wonderment

00:40:19.933 --> 00:40:22.333
because how could we do
something like this today,

00:40:22.333 --> 00:40:23.067
it's not clear.

00:40:23.067 --> 00:40:27.233
But at least we have this
example of how environmental

00:40:27.233 --> 00:40:31.400
science can prevent
these problems.

